{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/mastering-paper/drawing-hair/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"frontmatter":{"title":"How to draw realistic hair with Paper for iOS","date":"2013-05-10T00:00:00.000Z","date_pretty":"May 10th, 2013","date_from_now":"7 years ago","last_modified_at":"2019-09-12T20:06:54.000Z","last_modified_at_from_now":"10 months ago","path":"/mastering-paper/drawing-hair/","author":null,"excerpt":"I'm often asked what my Paper techniques for drawing hair is. Learn what they are in this short tutorial.","tags":["Paper for iOS","tutorial","Apple"],"image":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"aspectRatio":3.4375,"src":"/static/1b3930eb022e00e5c3792a384407a8e6/fc20c/how-to-draw-hair-feature.jpg","srcSet":"/static/1b3930eb022e00e5c3792a384407a8e6/6e883/how-to-draw-hair-feature.jpg 275w,\n/static/1b3930eb022e00e5c3792a384407a8e6/a09ef/how-to-draw-hair-feature.jpg 550w,\n/static/1b3930eb022e00e5c3792a384407a8e6/fc20c/how-to-draw-hair-feature.jpg 1100w,\n/static/1b3930eb022e00e5c3792a384407a8e6/356ef/how-to-draw-hair-feature.jpg 1280w","sizes":"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px"},"fixed":{"src":"/static/1b3930eb022e00e5c3792a384407a8e6/fc20c/how-to-draw-hair-feature.jpg","height":321,"width":1100}}},"toc":true,"comments":true,"comments_locked":true,"hide_meta":null},"id":"566ee704-4676-50a5-b2d5-ba52b17f4dd0","html":"<h2 id=\"block-out-the-hair\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#block-out-the-hair\" aria-label=\"block out the hair permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Block out the hair</h2>\n<p>I like to rough out a general shape of the subject’s hair using watercolor loaded with black or dark brown. Depending on what the overall palette is I might adjust the brown — usually mixing in red to warm it up or blue to cool it down.</p>\n<p>When working with the watercolor brush remember to <strong>layer</strong> numerous strokes to get a rich dark base. Just painting one coat of black won’t give great results needed for the next step.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1100px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 74.9090909090909%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"Drawing hair with Paper for iOS cheatsheet\"\n        title=\"Drawing hair with Paper for iOS cheatsheet\"\n        data-src=\"/static/4f1a8c4ff77e739cf104aada4b4c35d0/eacc7/drawing-hair-paper-53-cheatsheet.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/4f1a8c4ff77e739cf104aada4b4c35d0/16841/drawing-hair-paper-53-cheatsheet.jpg 275w,\n/static/4f1a8c4ff77e739cf104aada4b4c35d0/50c97/drawing-hair-paper-53-cheatsheet.jpg 550w,\n/static/4f1a8c4ff77e739cf104aada4b4c35d0/eacc7/drawing-hair-paper-53-cheatsheet.jpg 1100w,\n/static/4f1a8c4ff77e739cf104aada4b4c35d0/cc4ba/drawing-hair-paper-53-cheatsheet.jpg 1650w,\n/static/4f1a8c4ff77e739cf104aada4b4c35d0/77bd5/drawing-hair-paper-53-cheatsheet.jpg 2048w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h2 id=\"draw-each-strand\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#draw-each-strand\" aria-label=\"draw each strand permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Draw each strand</h2>\n<p>The key here is observation — look at how each strand(or section) of hair moves, where they start, and where they end. Using the pencil draw each strand of hair from root to tip, following the same paths you observed. For these initial strokes use mid tones to shape the major hair sections and parts. Then gradually brighten the color as you draw in hair with highlights. Adding small strokes of white and light yellow can really bring life to the hair, just be careful not to over do it.</p>\n<p>For those new to the app I suggest drawing in grays — limiting your palette to get a feel for the tools and how they behave. Working with a limitless selection of color could complicate and distract you from learning the tools. Thankfully FiftyThree’s excellent color mixer <em>just works</em> when you’re ready to exploit it.</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 600px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 57.81818181818181%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"Paper&apos;s default palette\" title=\"Paper&apos;s default palette\" data-src=\"/static/2dffed82ebfb11ceb387b41a8a867033/f6133/paper-default-hair-palette-600.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/2dffed82ebfb11ceb387b41a8a867033/16841/paper-default-hair-palette-600.jpg 275w,\n/static/2dffed82ebfb11ceb387b41a8a867033/50c97/paper-default-hair-palette-600.jpg 550w,\n/static/2dffed82ebfb11ceb387b41a8a867033/f6133/paper-default-hair-palette-600.jpg 600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p>The browns in this default palette are good to start with before mixing your own.</p></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>On the subject of palettes… I stick with the default sets. Since I draw a ton of portraits, it’s much quicker for me to adjust a color on the fly. But I do see the benefit of setting up a predetermined palette beforehand to give your illustration a feeling of cohesion. Before the color mixer existed you had to get inventive if you wanted additional colors. A limitation that encouraged experimentation and sometimes unexpected results.</p>\n<p>The following are some of my favorite color presets for drawing hair:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1006px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 65.45454545454545%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"Paper 53 color for red hair base\"\n        title=\"Paper 53 color for red hair base\"\n        data-src=\"/static/1dbc1d356ed4b67f516eb9c1efad3a10/615ae/paper-53-color-redheads-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/1dbc1d356ed4b67f516eb9c1efad3a10/16841/paper-53-color-redheads-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/1dbc1d356ed4b67f516eb9c1efad3a10/50c97/paper-53-color-redheads-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/1dbc1d356ed4b67f516eb9c1efad3a10/615ae/paper-53-color-redheads-lg.jpg 1006w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1006px) 100vw, 1006px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1006px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 65.45454545454545%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"Paper 53 color for brunette highlights\"\n        title=\"Paper 53 color for brunette highlights\"\n        data-src=\"/static/a257f79b00472b9871523dabaf2c22ae/615ae/paper-53-color-brunettes-highlight-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/a257f79b00472b9871523dabaf2c22ae/16841/paper-53-color-brunettes-highlight-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/a257f79b00472b9871523dabaf2c22ae/50c97/paper-53-color-brunettes-highlight-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/a257f79b00472b9871523dabaf2c22ae/615ae/paper-53-color-brunettes-highlight-lg.jpg 1006w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1006px) 100vw, 1006px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1006px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 65.45454545454545%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"Paper 53 color watercolor shading\"\n        title=\"Paper 53 color watercolor shading\"\n        data-src=\"/static/14d353a6b3e69311c0a8189c436622f2/615ae/paper-53-color-watercolor-shading-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/14d353a6b3e69311c0a8189c436622f2/16841/paper-53-color-watercolor-shading-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/14d353a6b3e69311c0a8189c436622f2/50c97/paper-53-color-watercolor-shading-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/14d353a6b3e69311c0a8189c436622f2/615ae/paper-53-color-watercolor-shading-lg.jpg 1006w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1006px) 100vw, 1006px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h2 id=\"dark-strokes-add-definition\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#dark-strokes-add-definition\" aria-label=\"dark strokes add definition permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Dark strokes add definition</h2>\n<p>Working an area too much with the pencil can cause your hair to flatten out. To fix this, draw dark pencil strokes over the problematic areas. If you follow the hair paths, drawing root to tip again — these dark strokes can help add detail back to the hair. Make your strokes quick and try not to go over the same line twice or else it might darken too much.</p>\n<h2 id=\"watercolor-for-dimension\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#watercolor-for-dimension\" aria-label=\"watercolor for dimension permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Watercolor for dimension</h2>\n<p>If you’re a maniac with the pencil and prefer to draw in all the gradations then feel free to omit this step. I’m much too lazy for that and prefer to paint over the strokes to achieve the same effect. A warm light gray works great for brunettes and a light orange or pink for redheads. Experimentation is the key here. If you don’t like the result just two finger rewind that noise and try another color. Lighter layers of watercolor that are built up gradually allow for subtler tones than a stroke of black would.</p>\n<div class=\"custom-block notice\"><div class=\"custom-block-heading\">Mastering Paper tutorials</div><div class=\"custom-block-body\"><p>Since publishing this short guide I’ve gone through several iPad styli and written numerous tutorials expanding on the techniques described above. | Be sure to check out my <a href=\"/mastering-paper/\"><strong>Mastering Paper by FiftyThree series</strong></a> to learn the latest ways I’m using the app and tools to create realistic portraits and other pieces of art. </p></div></div>","excerpt":"Block out the hair I like to rough out a general shape of the subject’s hair using watercolor loaded with black or dark brown. Depending on…","timeToRead":2,"tableOfContents":"<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/drawing-hair/#block-out-the-hair\">Block out the hair</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/drawing-hair/#draw-each-strand\">Draw each strand</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/drawing-hair/#dark-strokes-add-definition\">Dark strokes add definition</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/mastering-paper/drawing-hair/#watercolor-for-dimension\">Watercolor for dimension</a></li>\n</ul>"},"comments":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"47204b08-b8ff-5fae-97fb-e45013272247","frontmatter":{"name":"LMM","email":null,"friendlyDate":"February 20, 2014","iso8601Date":"2014-02-20T13:30:55.000Z","published":null},"html":"<p>Outstanding! Thank you so much :)</p>"}},{"node":{"id":"00dcb0cf-daec-5565-b9d4-fd5080e6b919","frontmatter":{"name":"Robert Hamm","email":null,"friendlyDate":"June 15, 2014","iso8601Date":"2014-06-15T01:08:58.000Z","published":null},"html":"<p>Really great info. This is the kind of tutorials I would have expected on 53’s\nsite. I’m so used to drawing with layers, that I’ve almost forgotten how to draw\nwithout them. Thanks for your info.</p>"}},{"node":{"id":"2bd841f5-853f-5e78-9366-51d3ca3ee16d","frontmatter":{"name":"Neehal Shaikh","email":"75fd94fc0eb1c2a8a54a324e835a3348","friendlyDate":"October 08, 2017","iso8601Date":"2017-10-08T14:37:17.364Z","published":null},"html":"<p>I have been following your page for quite a while now. I should say, you’ve\nhelped me lot. :) I have made some paintings too.\n<a href=\"https://goworkeatout.com/2017/10/07/a-lady-in-snow/\">https://goworkeatout.com/2017/10/07/a-lady-in-snow/</a> You got a great page, please\nkeep sharing the knowledge.</p>"}}]}},"pageContext":{"next":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/paperfaces/toblr-portrait/","title":"Hold the iPhone steady as you frame your shot","categories":["paperfaces"],"tags":["portrait","illustration","Paper for iOS"]},"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/28041/opensource/github.com/mmistakes/made-mistakes-gatsby/src/posts/paperfaces/toblr-portrait.md"},"previous":{"frontmatter":{"path":"/paperfaces/xoalexo-portrait/","title":"Muted tones in a cozy sweater","categories":["paperfaces"],"tags":["portrait","illustration","Paper for iOS","beard"]},"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/28041/opensource/github.com/mmistakes/made-mistakes-gatsby/src/posts/paperfaces/xoalexo-portrait.md"}}}}